data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *both* values, unlike `IsTrue`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — built-in collection helpers:
  - `AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `Contains(collection, item)`
  - `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order
  - `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — any order
  - `IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)`
- **Message parameters** — always pass a message string to `Assert.IsTrue` so failures are diagnosable

**Tip:** If you want even richer collection assertions, consider adding [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com):

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
